- Distractors align with common comma errors: 
  A) missing comma before coordinating conjunction in a compound sentence; 
  C) comma misplaced after the conjunction; 
  D) comma incorrectly splitting within the first clause (after verb “finished”).
- These are plausible and diagnostic for the target skill.

Distractors map to common errors: 
- A) misreading details to assume dislike; 
- B) overgeneralization (assuming professional status from hobby behavior);
- D) ignoring explicit content (flowers vs vegetables/herbs).

Distractors represent plausible, common errors: 
- B: lacks serial comma and introductory comma; 
- C: has introductory comma but missing list commas; 
- D: no commas at all. These choices diagnose whether students know commas in a series and introductory comma usage.
